    published_date: '2026-04-28',
    author: 'Andrew Smith',
    body: `I am not a developer. I have never written production code. I took a computer science subject at university in 2009 and dropped it after four weeks. I mention this not to build credibility but to provide context for what follows.\n\nOver the past twelve months, working as a UX Manager inside a product organisation, I built:\n\n— A Slack bot that searches simultaneously across our Figma design system, our Miro journey maps, and our GitHub documentation repository and returns synthesised answers in natural language.\n\n— A React application deployed to GitHub Pages that serves as our journey management platform, populated from FigJam data.\n\n— A full documentation site, also deployed to GitHub Pages, with our design system specifications.\n\n— A set of automations that run nightly checks comparing our Figma components against the production site and flagging discrepancies in Slack.\n\nNone of this involved writing code myself. All of it was built using Claude, in conversation.\n\n**What this is not**\n\nThis is not a story about AI replacing developers. The builds above represent genuine engineering work — it was just engineering work I did not perform personally. Claude performed it on my instruction.\n\nThis is also not a story about the power of AI in the abstract. Most articles about AI and work are either breathlessly positive or anxiously negative, and neither is useful. This is a specific account of specific tools built for a specific design team, with specific observations about what worked and what did not.\n\n**The Slack bot**\n\nThe starting point was a question we got repeatedly from product managers and engineers: "Is this component in the design system?" The answer required opening Figma, navigating to the relevant page, searching the component library, and either finding the component or confirming it did not exist. This took 3–7 minutes per query and interrupted whoever was asked.\n\nI described this problem to Claude and asked it to design a solution. It proposed a Slack bot connected to the Figma API that could answer the question in natural language. It wrote the code, explained what each part did, and helped me debug it when it did not work the first time.\n\nThe first version took two evenings. It could answer questions about specific component names. The second version, built the following week, could answer questions about component specifications — border radius, spacing tokens, colour values. The third version added the Miro connection, so it could also answer questions about journey map content.\n\nThe bot now handles approximately forty queries per week. Not one of them required a designer to open Figma.\n\n**What surprised me most**\n\nThe builds were technically impressive. But the thing that surprised me most was not technical — it was conceptual.\n\nBuilding the AI layer forced me to think very precisely about the structure of our design knowledge. For the bot to answer questions well, the design system had to be well-organised. The component names had to be consistent. The specifications had to be documented. The journey maps had to be labelled in a way that made the content findable.\n\nIn other words, the AI layer could only be as good as the underlying operating model. A team with good governance and good documentation practices got enormous value from the AI layer. A team without those things would have gotten noise.\n\nThis is why the Studio Method always installs the operating model before the AI layer. The filter gate, the pathways, the ceremonies, the design system governance — these are the foundations the AI layer is built on. Skip them and the AI layer amplifies chaos. Build them first and the AI layer amplifies quality.\n\n**The lesson**\n\nDesign operations is a knowledge management problem. Design teams generate knowledge — about users, about the product, about design decisions, about what worked and what did not — and most of that knowledge evaporates. It lives in people's heads, in old Slack threads, in Figma files that nobody opens after the handover.\n\nThe AI orchestration layer is the infrastructure that stops knowledge evaporating. It makes the design team's knowledge accessible, queryable, and useful — not just to the designers, but to everyone who works alongside them.\n\nAnd it can be built with prompts.`,
